ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[2] China - Guangdong
Date: Sat 3 May 2008
Source: China View Xinhua News Agency [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-05/03/content_8095003.htm>


A suspected [fatal] case of hand foot and mouth disease (HFMD) was
reported in south China's Guangdong Province, the provincial health
department announced early Saturday morning [3 May 2008]. The case
was reported in Gaoming district of Foshan city on Friday, and the
victim was an 18-month-old boy who died at 10 a.m. Friday, after he
got ill on 27 Apr 2008, the Guangdong Provincial Health Department
said in a statement. The case was probably caused by the intestinal
virus known as enterovirus 71 (EV71) according to the instant
[provisional] sample examination from the provincial disease
prevention control center. Further examination is underway. EV71 can
cause HFMD, which usually starts with a slight fever followed by
blisters and ulcers in the mouth and rashes on hands and feet.

Another suspected [fatal] case of the disease by preliminary clinical
diagnosis was reported in Gaoming district on 25 Apr 2008 according
to the health department. The department sent experts to Gaoming on
Friday [2 May 2008] morning to guide the disease control work. The
health bureau of Foshan city has carried out a daily report system of
the disease since Thursday.

The death toll from a mass intestinal virus infection rose to 22 in
Fuyang city in the eastern Anhui Province since early March 2008.
Central China's Hubei Province has seen 340 cases of HFMD this year
[2008], but no deaths have been reported, local health authorities
said Friday [2 May 2008].

HFMD, [can also be caused by] coxsackieviruses infection and is a
common childhood illness that mainly affects children under 10.
Symptoms include fever, sores in the mouth and a rash with blisters.
It often begins with a sore throat. Moderately contagious, the
disease, more common in summer and autumn, can be transmitted through
nose and throat discharges. Infection can lead to high death rates in
serious cases, and no vaccines are available.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

******
[3] Asia - China, Singapore and Viet Nam
Date: Sun 4 May 2008
Source: Associated Press report [edited]
<http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5j6YZgewXM0erJy6g9-0PWZo0unYAD90EPKBG0>


A common illness that typically causes little more than a fever and
rash has killed 24 children in China, and health officials fear the
worst may be yet to come as outbreaks occur in neighboring countries.
China's Health Ministry issued a nationwide alert over the weekend
after enterovirus 71 (EV-71), which causes hand, foot and mouth
disease (HFMD), infected more than 4500 children in central Anhui
province. The outbreak is centered around Fuyang city, where 22
deaths have occurred. On Sunday [4 May 2008], the official Xinhua
News Agency said the virus had claimed the lives of 2 more children
in southern Guangdong province.

"That's an extraordinarily high case fatality rate, and that's what
caught our attention," said Peter Cordingley, spokesman for the World
Health Organization's regional Western Pacific office. "Otherwise, it
would have passed under the radar." WHO issued a warning last week
predicting that the outbreak will likely continue in China for the
next few months because the virus tends to thrive in hot weather. It
advised disinfection and frequent hand washing to prevent its spread,
along with closing schools and daycare centers in hard-hit areas.

The outbreak in China comes as the country gears up for the Olympic
Games. WHO's Troedsson said the disease should not disrupt the
Beijing games, which start 8 Aug 2008. "I don't see it at all as a
threat to the Olympics or any upcoming events... This is a disease
mainly affecting young children," he said. But experts worry that the
more severe virus is becoming more common. Viet Nam and Singapore
have both recently seen a sharp increase in cases, including ones
linked to EV-71.

Viet Nam
---------
"On average, several children die from the disease each month at the
hospital," said Dr. Nguyen Quang Vinh at Children's Hospital No. 1 in
Viet Nam's southern Ho Chi Minh City. "Those children die not because
they are admitted to the hospital late, but because their disease
develops fast and attacks the brain and heart."

The number of cases reported nationwide this year [2008] in Viet Nam
was not immediately available, but state-run media have reported that
some children's hospitals have seen increases of up to 7 times over
last year [2007].

Singapore
---------
Infections also continue to rise in Singapore, which has reported
more than 9000 cases this year [2008], with EV-71 found in 25 percent
of the samples tested. No deaths have been reported in the wealthy
city-state, but the government has ordered 11 preschools and
child-care centers closed, according to the Health Ministry's website.

[Byline: Margie Mason]

