******
[4] China - 6 provinces now affected
Date: Sun 4 May 2008
Source: Shanghaiist.com [edited]
<http://shanghaiist.com/2008/05/05/hfmd_in_six_provinces.php>


Since hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD) 1st hit Fuyang in Anhui
Province, more cases have been reported in at least 5 other
provinces: Zhejiang, Henan, Hubei, Jiangxi and Guangdong.

622 new cases of the intestinal [virus infection] were reported in
Anhui on Saturday [3 May 2008], bringing the total number of cases to
5151. 22 children have died in Fuyang, and all kindergartens have
been ordered shut.

In Foshan city, Guangdong Province, a 3rd child has died from the
disease. Jiangxi Province has 21 recorded cases, but no deaths have
yet been reported. Neither Shanghai nor our neighboring Jiangsu
Province have any reported HFMD cases yet.

Although it is still too early to tell whether the epidemic has
peaked, the World Health Organization does not think it will be a
threat to the Olympics.

[This report contains an excellent photograph of the condition. - Mod.CP]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[The current EV71-associated outbreak of HFMD is affecting children
throughout East Asia, with the largest number of cases reported from
Singapore, but no deaths. In China, the central provinces of Anhui
and Hubei and southern Guangdong have been worst affected so far.
Fuyang City in Anhui has been the hardest hit, with the number of
cases climbing to 5151 with 22 fatalities. No fatalities have been
reported from Hubei, but 3 suspected deaths have been reported now
from the southern province of Guangdong. The reason for the high case
fatality rate in Fuyang city has not yet been determined.

A map of the provinces of China is available at
<http://www.chinamapxl.com/political-map.html>.
HealthMap interactive maps of Singapore and Viet Nam can be accessed at
<http://healthmap.org/promedv=1.4,103.8,6.> and
<http://healthmap.org/promed?v=14.9,108.5,5>,
respectively. - Mod.CP]
